it might be better to avoid using @Bean and only utilize @TestBean to create new beans. This way, I can focus on field injection and ensure the application context contains the necessary beans. However, if there's no configuration, loading it might result in issues like \\\"Could not detect default resource locations.\\\" Even with @ContextConfiguration pointing to an empty class, it still involves config reflection.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing Java Assertions**\\n\\nI'm noticing an assertion issue with a NullPointerException (NPE). But, I see the spring-beans are available, so the listener is good. I wonder if the `messageService` field is private; could the assertion from the enclosing class access the synthetic method? Java does allow that. I think I need to add a test, but I haven't run it yet. Should I mention unrelated items? Hmm, maybe it's best to keep things concise for now.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "Implemented a focused coverage test for the active class.\n\nAdded:\n- `tests/src/org.springframework/spring-test/7.0.0/src/test/java/org_springframework/spring_test/TestBeanOverrideHandlerTest.java`\n\nWhat it covers:\n- Uses Spring’s public `TestContextManager` + `@ContextConfiguration` flow.\n- Declares a `@TestBean` field with a matching private static factory method.\n- Preparing the test context causes `TestBeanOverrideHandler.createOverrideInstance()` to invoke the factory method, reaching:\n  - `java.lang.reflect.Method#invoke(...)`\n- Verifies both the injected `@TestBean` field and an application bean receive the override instance.\n\nI did not run tests, per instruction.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_01d97f72582ac1af016a29f358c36481978355db35dce2f905\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 355, "output": 955, "cacheRead": 33792, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 35102, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWr